Ultrasonic Distance Measurement with LCD and Buzzer

This project measures distance using an ultrasonic sensor and displays the value on a 16×2 LCD.
A buzzer plays a simple ascending scale melody each time the measurement is taken.

This project helps beginners learn:
-Using an ultrasonic sensor (HC-SR04) with Arduino
-Measuring distance with pulseIn
-Displaying values on a 16×2 LCD using LiquidCrystal
-Generating tones with a buzzer using tone
-Combining sensors, display, and sound in a single project

Arduino Code
#include <LiquidCrystal.h>

// LCD pins
int rs = 7;
int en = 8;
int d4 = 9;
int d5 = 10;
int d6 = 11;
int d7 = 12;

LiquidCrystal lcd(rs, en, d4, d5, d6, d7);

// Ultrasonic sensor pins
int trigPin = 5;
int echoPin = 3;
float traveltime;
float distance;

// Buzzer pin
int buzzPin = 2;

int dts = 500;

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(9600);
  pinMode(trigPin, OUTPUT);
  pinMode(echoPin, INPUT);
  pinMode(buzzPin, OUTPUT);

  lcd.begin(16, 2);
  delay(dts);
}

void loop() {
  // Trigger ultrasonic sensor
  digitalWrite(trigPin, LOW);
  delayMicroseconds(10);
  digitalWrite(trigPin, HIGH);
  delayMicroseconds(10);
  digitalWrite(trigPin, LOW);

  traveltime = pulseIn(echoPin, HIGH);
  distance = (traveltime / 2) / 29.1; // Convert to cm
  Serial.println(distance);

  // Display on LCD
  lcd.setCursor(0, 0);
  lcd.print("Distance is about");
  lcd.setCursor(0, 1);
  lcd.print(distance);
  lcd.setCursor(9, 1);
  lcd.print("cm");

  delay(10000); // Wait 10 seconds

  // Play ascending scale on buzzer
  tone(buzzPin, 262, 200); // DO
  delay(200);
  tone(buzzPin, 294, 200); // RE
  delay(200);
  tone(buzzPin, 330, 200); // MI
  delay(200);
  tone(buzzPin, 349, 200); // FA
  delay(200);
  tone(buzzPin, 392, 200); // SOL
  delay(200);
  tone(buzzPin, 440, 200); // LA
  delay(200);
  tone(buzzPin, 494, 200); // SI
  delay(200);
  tone(buzzPin, 523, 400); // High DO
}

Circuit Setup

Components needed:
Arduino Uno (or compatible board)
1 × HC-SR04 ultrasonic sensor
1 × 16×2 LCD
1 × Buzzer
Breadboard
Jumper wires

Wiring Instructions:

Ultrasonic Sensor
Trig → pin 5
Echo → pin 3
VCC → 5V
GND → GND

LCD
RS → pin 7
EN 
D4 → pin 9
D5 → pin 10
D6 → pin 11
D7 → pin 12
VCC → 5V
GND → GND

Buzzer
Positive → pin 2
Negative → GND

How it works:
The ultrasonic sensor measures the distance to an object using sound waves.
Distance is calculated and displayed on the LCD every 10 seconds.
After each reading, the buzzer plays an ascending musical scale to indicate the measurement was taken.
